**Idea:**

Since the sum of two numbers is even when both are even or both are odd, we can simply count the number of even numbers (even_counteven\_counteven_count) and odd numbers (odd_countodd\_countodd_count) in the array. The number of pairs that can be formed from the even numbers is

even_count×(even_count−1)2\frac{even\_count \times (even\_count - 1)}{2}2even_count×(even_count−1)​

and similarly for the odd numbers. The final answer is the sum of these two values.

**Time Complexity:**

O(N)O(N)O(N) per test case.

**C++ Implementation:**

`#include &lt;bits/stdc++.h&gt;
using namespace std;

int main() {
    int t;
    cin &gt;&gt; t;
    while(t--){
        int n;
        cin &gt;&gt; n;
        long long evenCount = 0, oddCount = 0;
        for (int i = 0; i &lt; n; i++){
            int num;
            cin &gt;&gt; num;
            if(num % 2 == 0)
                evenCount++;
            else
                oddCount++;
        }
        long long evenPairs = (evenCount * (evenCount - 1)) / 2;
        long long oddPairs = (oddCount * (oddCount - 1)) / 2;
        cout &lt;&lt; evenPairs + oddPairs &lt;&lt; "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
